==English==

===Etymology===
From the days of [[flintlock]] and [[caplock]] [[firearm]]s, where the half-cock position of the hammer was both a rudimentary safety, and the proper position for [[prime|priming]] the [[pan]] or inserting a percussion [[cap]].  The phrase was originally rendered, "to go off at half-cock."

===Noun===
'''[[go off]] [[half-cock]]ed'''
# {{idiom}} {{colloquial}} {{US}}:  To take a premature or ill-considered action.
#: ''Make sure none of your men '''go off half-cocked''' and ruin this operation.''

